<DocsLayout title="Writing the PRD" description="Use the prompt and template to create the Vinyl Vault requirements document.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Writing the PRD</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">You've done this before in Project 3. Same process: get the template from <a href="/templates">/templates</a>, paste the prompt below into Claude (the chat interface), review the output, iterate, then check with the client.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">The guidance here is briefer than P3's — you know the steps. The emphasis is on what to watch for in the review.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The prompt</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Paste this into Claude along with the PRD template:</p>

  <CodeBlock copy>{`You are a product manager writing a PRD for a small development agency. Use the template provided.

## Client Brief

Client: Marcus, owner of Vinyl Vault Records — a small vinyl record shop in Fitzroy, Melbourne.

Marcus currently sells via Discogs marketplace but wants his own online store for more control, better margins, and proper branding.

What Marcus wants:
- Browse records by artist or genre
- Search for specific records
- Add items to a shopping cart
- Pay with a card (Stripe — he doesn't want to handle card numbers)
- A map showing the physical shop location (Fitzroy, Melbourne)
- Clean, simple store experience

What Marcus explicitly does NOT want:
- No subscriptions or membership tiers
- No auctions
- No user reviews or ratings
- No wishlists or saved items
- No user accounts (guest checkout only)
- No Discogs integration or sync
- No blog or news section
- No live chat

Tech stack: React frontend, FastAPI backend, PostgreSQL, Stripe for payments, Google Maps for store location, Docker, GitHub Actions CI, Gemini reviewer.

Write the PRD using the template. Focus on what Marcus asked for. Do not add features he didn't request — online stores are a common pattern and you'll be tempted to add standard e-commerce features. Resist that.`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Review the output</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same review principles as P3, with one new emphasis:</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Watch for e-commerce scope creep</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Online stores are heavily represented in AI training data. AI will try to add features Marcus never asked for. Check the PRD for:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Saved cards or payment methods</strong> — Marcus said guest checkout. No accounts means no saved payment info.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Product recommendations</strong> — "Customers who bought this also bought..." was never mentioned.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Discount codes or coupons</strong> — not in the brief.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Inventory management UI</strong> — Marcus will manage this himself. The store just displays what's available.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Email marketing</strong> — order confirmation yes, newsletters no.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Ratings or reviews</strong> — explicitly ruled out.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">Abandoned cart recovery</strong> — guest checkout, no accounts, no way to follow up.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Check the acceptance criteria</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same standards as P3 — specific, verifiable, no vague language. For payment-related criteria, they should reference Stripe test mode specifically (e.g., "payment completes with Stripe test card 4242 4242 4242 4242").</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Iterate and check with the client</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">Refine the PRD until it captures exactly what Marcus asked for — no more, no less. Then present it to the client (or review it as if you were Marcus). Would he recognise what's described? Would he spot anything he didn't ask for?</p>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: requirements documentation</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">You're writing a PRD — a product requirements document. It's one of several ways to capture what needs to be built.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">PRDs</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Product requirements documents. Feature-focused, written by product managers. What you're using in this project. Good for communicating the "what" and "why" to stakeholders.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">User Stories</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">"As a [user], I want [feature] so that [benefit]." Short, focused on user value. Common in Agile teams. Often live on cards in Jira or Linear.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Jobs-to-be-Done (JTBD)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Focuses on what the user is trying to accomplish, not features. "When I want to buy a record, I want to pay without creating an account." Helps avoid building features nobody needs.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Behaviour-Driven Development (BDD)</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">"Given [context], when [action], then [outcome]." Requirements written as executable specifications. Tools like Cucumber turn these into automated tests.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">Acceptance Criteria</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Specific, testable conditions that a feature must meet. Often attached to user stories. "Payment completes with test card 4242 4242 4242 4242" is an acceptance criterion.</span></p></div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">PRDs work well for this project because you're capturing a complete product scope. In a team setting, you'd likely combine PRDs with user stories and acceptance criteria. The format matters less than the discipline of writing requirements before writing code.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

